{"title_page": "Aivars Lembergs", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image         =Aivars Lembergs 2017.jpg\n| name          =Aivars Lembergs\n| order         =Mayor of Ventspils\n| term_start    =1988\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   =\n| successor     =\n| birth_date    ={{Birth date and age|1953|09|26|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[J\u0113kabpils]], [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic]], [[USSR]]\n| death_place   =\n| party         =[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] <small>(1975 - 1990)</small><br />[[For Latvia and Ventspils]] <small>(since 1994)</small>\n| spouse        =In\u0101ra Lemberga \n|blank1       = Net worth\n|data1        = {{Increase}} US$270 [[1000000 (number)|million]] (2013)<ref>{{cite web |title =The Lembergs still Latvia's wealthiest family in 2013 |publisher = [[The Baltic Course]] |year =2013 |url =http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/analytics/?doc=836817 |accessdate =June 28, 2014}}</ref>\n|children     = Anrijs<br />Liga\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Latvia]]\n|website      = [http://www.aivarslembergs.lv/ www.aivarslembergs.lv]\n| signature =\n| occupation = Politician\n}}\n\n'''Aivars Lembergs''' (born September 26, 1953) is a [[Latvia]]n [[politician]] and [[Business oligarch|oligarch]], who has been the [[mayor]] of [[Ventspils]] since 1988. \n\n==Early life==\nLembergs was born in [[J\u0113kabpils]], Latvia. He studied [[economics]] in Latvian State University (now known as the [[University of Latvia]]), graduating in 1977. He then worked in various positions in the [[Communist party of Latvia]], becoming mayor of Ventspils in 1988. He stayed in this position after Latvia became independent and has been re-elected five times. Lembergs was the leader of the local political party, ''[[Latvijai un Ventspilij]]'' (\"For Latvia and Ventspils\") which he founded in 1994. ''Latvijai un Ventspilij'' has completely dominated the city politics since it was founded. \n\nBefore the 2006 parliamentary election, Lembergs' party ''Latvijai and Ventspilij'' entered into an alliance with the [[Union of Greens and Farmers]] and the Union of Greens and Farmers named Lembergs as its candidate for the Prime Minister of Latvia. He remains its leading figure and chief financial supporter.<ref>{{cite book |title=Nations in Transit 2007: Democratization from Central Europe to Eurasia |last=Goehring |first=Jeannette |year=2007 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |location=London |isbn=978-0-932088-26-0 |pages=404 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drjJRxs2HRMC |accessdate=}}</ref> He is one of the three \"oligarchs\" against which [[Zatlers' Reform Party]] had pledged to act if it achieves office.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-18/latvian-parties-agree-on-budget-euro-as-coalition-talks-begin.html Eglitis, Aaron. \"Latvian Parties Agree Budget, Euro as Coalition Talks Begin\"] ''[[Bloomberg.com]]'' September 19, 2011</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nSince 2008 he has faced a long-running investigation for [[bribery]], [[money laundering]] and abuse of office; he vehemently denies all wrongdoing.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2011/09/latvian-elections-oligarchs-exit E.L. \"Time up for tycoons; Latvian elections: the oligarchs' exit\" ''[[The Economist]]'' September 13, 2011]</ref><ref>http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?docid=178741&doclang=en ''[[European Court of Justice]]'' May 25, 2016</ref><ref name=\"Jemberga\">{{cite news |last1=Jemberga |first1=Sanita |title=New Panama leak sheds light on the wealth of Latvian oligarch\u2019s daughter |url=https://en.rebaltica.lv/2018/07/new-panama-leak-sheds-light-on-the-wealth-of-a-latvian-oligarchs-daughter/ |accessdate=24 July 2018 |publisher=[[Re:Baltica]] |date=13 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LSM-7Mar2019\">{{cite news |title=Prosecutor demands 8-year jail sentence for Ventspils bigwig |url=https://eng.lsm.lv/article/society/crime/prosecutor-demands-8-year-jail-sentence-for-ventspils-bigwig.a311944/ |accessdate=9 March 2019 |work=eng.lsm.lv |agency=LETA |publisher=[[Public Broadcasting of Latvia|Latvian Public Broadcasting]] |date=7 March 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Controversies==\n\nLembergs also featured in the 2016 [[Panama papers]] offshore scandal.<ref>[http://www.baltictimes.com/latvian_public_figures_feature_in_panama_papers \"Latvian public figures feature in Panama papers\"] [[The Baltic Times]] April 7, 2016</ref>. On December 9, 2019, the US government blocked his US assets under the Magnitsky Act<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mengqi |first1=Sun |title=U.S. Blacklists Foreign Officials, Support Networks for Alleged Corruption |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-blacklists-foreign-officials-support-networks-for-alleged-corruption-11575931212 |accessdate=10 December 2019 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=9 December 2019}}</ref>. \n\nOn 10 December 2019, the US State Department declared him, his wife and children ineligible for entry into the US<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Designations Due to Significant Corruption of Latvian and Cambodian Officials |url=https://www.state.gov/public-designations-due-to-significant-corruption-of-latvian-and-cambodian-officials/ |website=state.gov |publisher=US Department of State | date=10 December 2019 |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>.\n\nOn 23 March 23 2020, [[Ventspils]] City Council deputy [[\u0122irts Valdis Kristovskis]] has turned to the State Police with a request to start a criminal process against Lembergs for his defamatory claims voiced against minority deputy and state official Kristovskis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bnn-news.com/criminal-process-launched-against-aivars-lembergs-for-defamation-212209|title=Criminal process launched against Aivars Lembergs for defamation|date=2020-04-08|website=Baltic News Network - News from Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lembergs, Aivars}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from J\u0113kabpils]]\n[[Category:People sanctioned under the Magnitsky Act]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Latvia politicians]]\n[[Category:For Latvia and Ventspils politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the Supreme Council of the Republic of Latvia]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Latvian businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image         =Aivars Lembergs 2017.jpg\n| name          =Aivars Lembergs\n| order         =Mayor of Ventspils\n| term_start    =1988\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   =\n| successor     =\n| birth_date    ={{Birth date and age|1953|09|26|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[J\u0113kabpils]], [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic]], [[USSR]]\n| death_place   =\n| party         =[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] <small>(1975 - 1990)</small><br />[[For Latvia and Ventspils]] <small>(since 1994)</small>\n| spouse        =In\u0101ra Lemberga \n|blank1       = Net worth\n|data1        = {{Increase}} US$270 [[1000000 (number)|million]] (2013)<ref>{{cite web |title =The Lembergs still Latvia's wealthiest family in 2013 |publisher = [[The Baltic Course]] |year =2013 |url =http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/analytics/?doc=836817 |accessdate =June 28, 2014}}</ref>\n|children     = Anrijs<br />Liga\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Latvia]]\n|website      = [http://www.aivarslembergs.lv/ www.aivarslembergs.lv]\n| signature =\n| occupation = Politician\n}}\n\n'''Aivars Lembergs''' (born September 26, 1953) is a [[Latvia]]n [[politician]] and [[Business oligarch|oligarch]], who has been the [[mayor]] of [[Ventspils]] since 1988. Since 2008 he has faced a long-running investigation for [[bribery]], [[money laundering]] and abuse of office; he vehemently denies all wrongdoing.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2011/09/latvian-elections-oligarchs-exit E.L. \"Time up for tycoons; Latvian elections: the oligarchs' exit\" ''[[The Economist]]'' September 13, 2011]</ref><ref>http://curia.europa.eu/juris/document/document.jsf?docid=178741&doclang=en ''[[European Court of Justice]]'' May 25, 2016</ref><ref name=\"Jemberga\">{{cite news |last1=Jemberga |first1=Sanita |title=New Panama leak sheds light on the wealth of Latvian oligarch\u2019s daughter |url=https://en.rebaltica.lv/2018/07/new-panama-leak-sheds-light-on-the-wealth-of-a-latvian-oligarchs-daughter/ |accessdate=24 July 2018 |publisher=[[Re:Baltica]] |date=13 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"LSM-7Mar2019\">{{cite news |title=Prosecutor demands 8-year jail sentence for Ventspils bigwig |url=https://eng.lsm.lv/article/society/crime/prosecutor-demands-8-year-jail-sentence-for-ventspils-bigwig.a311944/ |accessdate=9 March 2019 |work=eng.lsm.lv |agency=LETA |publisher=[[Public Broadcasting of Latvia|Latvian Public Broadcasting]] |date=7 March 2019}}</ref> Lembergs also featured in the 2016 [[Panama papers]] offshore scandal.<ref>[http://www.baltictimes.com/latvian_public_figures_feature_in_panama_papers \"Latvian public figures feature in Panama papers\"] [[The Baltic Times]] April 7, 2016</ref>. On December 9, 2019, the US government blocked his US assets under the Magnitsky Act<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mengqi |first1=Sun |title=U.S. Blacklists Foreign Officials, Support Networks for Alleged Corruption |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-blacklists-foreign-officials-support-networks-for-alleged-corruption-11575931212 |accessdate=10 December 2019 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=9 December 2019}}</ref>. On December 10, 2019, the US State Department declared him, his wife and children ineligible for entry into the US<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Designations Due to Significant Corruption of Latvian and Cambodian Officials |url=https://www.state.gov/public-designations-due-to-significant-corruption-of-latvian-and-cambodian-officials/ |website=state.gov |publisher=US Department of State | date=10 December 2019 |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>.\n\nLembergs was born in [[J\u0113kabpils]], Latvia. He studied [[economics]] in Latvian State University (now known as the [[University of Latvia]]), graduating in 1977. He then worked in various positions in the [[Communist party of Latvia]], becoming mayor of Ventspils in 1988. He stayed in this position after Latvia became independent and has been re-elected five times. Lembergs was the leader of the local political party, ''[[Latvijai un Ventspilij]]'' (\"For Latvia and Ventspils\") which he founded in 1994. ''Latvijai un Ventspilij'' has completely dominated the city politics since it was founded. Before the 2006 parliamentary election, Lembergs' party ''Latvijai and Ventspilij'' entered into an alliance with the [[Union of Greens and Farmers]] and the Union of Greens and Farmers named Lembergs as its candidate for the Prime Minister of Latvia. He remains its leading figure and chief financial supporter.<ref>{{cite book |title=Nations in Transit 2007: Democratization from Central Europe to Eurasia |last=Goehring |first=Jeannette |year=2007 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |location=London |isbn=978-0-932088-26-0 |pages=404 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drjJRxs2HRMC |accessdate=}}</ref> He is one of the three \"oligarchs\" against which [[Zatlers' Reform Party]] had pledged to act if it achieves office.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-18/latvian-parties-agree-on-budget-euro-as-coalition-talks-begin.html Eglitis, Aaron. \"Latvian Parties Agree Budget, Euro as Coalition Talks Begin\" ''[[Bloomberg.com]]'' September 19, 2011]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lembergs, Aivars}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from J\u0113kabpils]]\n[[Category:People sanctioned under the Magnitsky Act]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Latvia politicians]]\n[[Category:For Latvia and Ventspils politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the Supreme Council of the Republic of Latvia]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Latvian businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Infogapp1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added sub-headings for easier readability", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aivars_Lembergs"}
